The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Weekend shows on varsity calendar
                                                                                                               Weekend shows on varsity calendar
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Gaya, Feb. 17: With 500-odd boys and girls participating in music, dance, drama, oration, cartoon and painting events at four venues spread over 600 acres that make up Magadh University (MU), the campus is at present abuzz with activities.        
	MU, earlier notorious for its gun culture, received a facelift for the Presidents visit.        
	On Saturday, Munshi Prem Chands Vinod was presented at the Renaissance cultural centre, with Manu Mani, Shivangi, Hasrat Khan and Kashif Iqbal in the lead roles. Rajesh Awasthi played the anchor in the play that was directed by Sanjay Sahay.         
	Artistes from Bihar universities were busy with street plays and mime on Saturday morning. The mime performance on corruption, non-recognition of merit and poverty-propelled crime held the audience captive.        
	A cartoon competition, with unholy medical practices as its theme was organised at venue No. 4 in the Central Library Hall on the same day.         
	English and Hindi debates on nuclear deal and television serials, respectively, were held on Sunday.        
	Krishna Kumar, officer on special duty in the chancellors office, has been working over time for the past four days  Tarang is his brainchild after all.         
	Talking to The Telegraph, he conceded that the fest was started to promote co-curricular and extra-curricular activities and shape the overall personality of each student  the ultimate objective of education.         
	In Tarang there would be cultural events to suit every taste. Indian classical and semi-classical music performances  with Anup Jalota and Ghulam Ali  is to follow soon. While most participants welcomed the shows, some said that by inviting celebrity performers the organisers were overshadowing emerging local talents.                                                                                                                                                                           
